# Agent Resources
[(back to project README)](../README.md)

## What's in this directory

Resource YAML files define Databricks resources deployed by the bundle:

| File | Resources |
|------|-----------|
| `app-resource.yml` | Databricks App — serves your agent via MLflow AgentServer |
| `agent-resource.yml` | Agent development job — trains/logs agent, runs evaluation with quality gates |
| `agents-artifacts-resource.yml` | MLflow registered model and experiment |
| `data-preparation-resource.yml` | Data pipeline job — ingestion, preprocessing, vector search index |

## How Databricks Asset Bundles work

Resources are defined as YAML and deployed together with your code via `databricks bundle deploy`. The CLI reads `databricks.yml` (the bundle root), resolves variable substitutions for the target environment, and creates or updates each resource in the workspace.

Key patterns:
- **`${bundle.target}`** — replaced with the target name (dev, staging, prod, test). Used in resource names to avoid collisions across environments.
- **`${var.variable_name}`** — bundle variables defined in `databricks.yml`. Override per-target under `targets.<name>.variables`.
- **`notebook_path`** — relative path from the resource YAML file to the notebook.

## Deployment targets

| Target | When | Catalog | Eval threshold |
|--------|------|---------|----------------|
| dev | Manual (`databricks bundle deploy -t dev`) | dev | relaxed |
| staging | Merge to `main` (via CI/CD) | staging | strict |
| prod | Merge to `release` (via CI/CD) | prod | strict |
| test | PR validation (via CI/CD) | test | relaxed |

To use different catalog names, set `uc_catalog` under each target in `databricks.yml`:

```yaml
targets:
  dev:
    variables:
      uc_catalog: my_dev_catalog
```

## Local development

### Authentication

Set up the Databricks CLI with a [personal access token]({{ template `generate_doc_link` (map (pair "cloud" .input_cloud) (pair "path" "dev-tools/auth/pat.html")) }}) or a [CLI profile](https://docs.databricks.com/en/dev-tools/cli/profiles.html):

```bash
export DATABRICKS_TOKEN=dapi...
```

Or configure a profile in `~/.databrickscfg` and reference it in `databricks.yml`.

### Validate and deploy

```bash
databricks bundle validate -t dev    # check config
databricks bundle deploy -t dev      # deploy resources
databricks bundle run agent_development_job -t dev  # run agent dev + eval
```

### Clean up

```bash
databricks bundle destroy -t dev
```

This removes bundle-managed resources (jobs, app, experiment, model). Data assets (tables, volumes, vector search indexes) are not managed by the bundle and must be removed manually if needed.

